If you don't know how to use a Ouija Board, check out http://paranormal.about.com/cs/ouijaboards/ht/use_ouija.htm for concise instructions. A printable Ouija Board can be found here http://www.wikihow.com/images/sampledocs/3/Ouija-Board.pdf (2D paper printable, not 3D plastic printable). This planchette has a removable front leg tip, which when removed, allows the leg to accommodate the tip of a pencil to allow the planchette to be used as an automatic writing device. I provide this printable model with the proviso that it is a toy for gaming and not a tool to speak to spirits. I am not responsible if the use of this item opens an inter-dimensional doorway to hell, releasing unspeakable horrors to amble the earth and feast on our flesh. Happy Halloween!!!

This is just a simple design that can be used for a number of things.  Most commonly the commercial equivalent of this is used to blow air or liquid over tools on CNC machines, drill presses, etc.  I am thinking of using it as an articulated arm to hold camera flashes off-camera and run wires through the center. EDIT:  I uploaded all three resolutions.  The highest is what made the links in the picture, but you may have similar luck with the other two resolutions.  Thanks!

title: Da Vinci 2.0: Quick! E3d V6 conversion

description.text:
These two small parts (cap and mount) can be used to convert your da vinci 2.0 duo to a single extruder E3d V6 without having to print an entirely carriage.

The cap does not need supports and I chose to print the mount with supports to minimize clean up. I also removed the second stepper motor on the carriage which has reduced weight significantly and has allowed me to print at 80mm/s without resonance in the x or y direction.

In Repetier EEPROM setting, I changed the lowered max z-axis by the difference in height between the original and the new nozzle. There is an optical end-stop sensor for the z-axis which is used to home the z-axis. there is a piece of metal on the bed which trips the end stop. I glued a piece of paper on to this, metal tab, to effectively extend the tab the distance of the which you changed the max z-axis travel. Sorry I don't have any pictures of this at the moment, I'm away from home for the next two weeks. You'll have to poke around your printer settings and take a look at the end stop to figure out what I mean.

also there is a small support in the bottom of the carriage which needs to be cut off to allow room for the cold end fan. The fan is 12v so I chose to run a line from the PSU which is turned on with the printer.

required materials:
about 10m of T-glase or ABS
2x m6x16mm (maybe 20mm?)
2x m6 nuts or nutserts

Version 2 of the mount is untested but should add extra stability to hot end although I haven't seen any need for it. If you test it, please let me know.

I have plans to convert to bowden to decrease weight further. Will update once I find the time.

description.text:
This is my attempt at making a custom mount for my Geeetech G2S printer to use the dual E3D V6 hotends with a Bowden connection. I tried several of the other plates on here, and while they are some great designs, it would cause my arms to no longer be parallel and rather than continue trying to add one fix on top of another, I figured I would try to just make a mount that is similar to the stock one, but that fits the new hotends.
I really disliked the stock hotends that came with this. It was so difficult to level them without taking the entire thing apart. So far on this one, you can only level them just by sticking a few shims in between the top piece and the 'spider' piece. I use parts of cut up paper.
If anyone has suggestions, please let me know, as I have not designed many functional things and I'm new to the whole delta design (I normally use an i3) so I am sure there are things that I didn't know to account for.

It just uses M3 nuts and bolts just like the stock mount.

V2:
-Made two different clamps to fit better. You will need one of each.
-Added screw and nut fittings in center of plates.

V3:
-Adjusted size of openings in both mounts

V4:
-Made bottom mount thicker to prevent vertical hotend movement
-Removed clamps, not enough room to fit with heatsink fins.
-Added small caps to the lower mount to help prevent horizontal hotend movement
--You will need to print two of the caps.

title: Oculus CV1 prescription fixed-frame（15mm vertex distance）

description.text:
The 15mm vertex distance frame( match my face).

The original one is definitely not suit for the "almost blind" people like me.
The lens are too far(vertex distance), No frame bridge(PD is not fixed).

For high index and high spherical lens.
The PD , VD and frame curve should be fixed , put it at right position precisely.
Update:

The "frame_solid.stl" is 43mm round frame with 28mm frame bridge. 6mm higher than the one i remixed from.This frame might touch your face.

The "frame_asian" is 45mm round frame with 21mm bridge.(Such frame can be easily found at most Asian glasses stores) . For smaller faces and PD like Asian males and females. 2mm lower than the one above.

The axis markers have been added on both frame.Help you fix cylinder-axis of your lens.

Vertex distance is important

I have tested multiple different designs. Most of them ,the lens are too close to the CV1.

Every 1 millimeter causes diopter shift. If the lens are too close to the CV1's fresnel lens . The diopter will shift like 0.5~1.0D compare with your prescriptions. And the higher diopter the smaller margin for error. Human eyes can adjust it self for small diopter errors. But it may gets tired very fast or causes sight problems.

The foam is soft , every face is unique, and the regular glasses cant be worn on the face for fixing distance. In such case, Measuring and tweaking are very necessary things if you want a perfect result.

Since the printer does not print so accurately I left some air between the two parts.
To the exact adjustment, I have the inner part with Teflonband wrapped up one layer, also the front side.
Now insert the tube halfway and add some hot glue to the end of the tube. Now compress the whole until the hot glue has cooled down. The Teflon tape prevents the two parts from sticking together and minimizes wear. When everything has cooled, remove the hot glue with a cutter. Now there should be enough friction and the parts do not fall apart on their own.

description.text:
Project #2 - Egg Drop

This project involves taking the classic egg drop experiment done in many general science and physics classrooms and puts a 3D printing spin on it. The sample STL file is only a sample of what can be designed to help house the egg and any other parts/pieces that will help support it.

As for restrictions on egg design, it can be up to the instructor to what extent students may design in 3D and/or add in terms of additional physical supports.

The sample 3D STL file included is borrowed from user: NathanSquire67,

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:471112

Printer:

Flashforge 3D Creator Pro

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.27

Infill:

15%

Notes:

The egg files attached MUST be scaled to 1.5 or higher to fit a regular sized egg. This project is better executed if students create their own designs.

I recommend that students customize their own 'Egg Shell' file that is big enough not only for the raw egg, but also for other supports that might be added such as paper, cardboard pieces, etc.

The custom case that the students design should be big enough to fit the egg in snugly so that it can be dropped from different heights! Additional Information

This current design is not sufficient to allow the survival of an egg at heights above 1 meter. In order to successfully create a protective shell for the egg, the use of a larger design with internal supports will be necessary. Extra support materials can include straws, cotton balls, paper, etc.

Students who are creating custom egg cases can use TinkerCAD, Sketchup, or any other 3D modeling program that can make STL files.

I used ReplicatorG to slice the files.
NGSS

Students in a physics/physical science setting will engage in a lab activity involving the design, construction (3D Printing), and testing their creation with a raw egg at specific drop heights. Students will utilize a tape measure, recording device, 3D modeling software, a 3D printer, and any necessary support materials. Skill Levels Recommended:
3D modeling: Basic/Intermediate
3D printing: Basic/Intermediate Objectives:
Students will be using their 3D printed shells to drop their eggs from specific heights (can be any particular/accessible height) and recording data on different physical quantities such as kinetic energy, potential energy, impulse, etc. Skills Learned (Standards):
HS-PS3-2. Develop and use models to illustrate that energy at the macroscopic scale can be accounted for as a combination of energy associated with the motions of particles (objects) and energy associated with the relative positions of particles (objects).

Step 1: Pass out lab worksheet and debrief instructions with students Step 2: Establish groups (3-4) Step 3: Allow students one hour to design their 3D egg shell. Step 4: Print out group egg shells (print them for the following class to test the shells) Step 5: Have students mass their egg shells with and without the raw eggs inside Step 6: Lead students to the egg drop area (tall area with heights labeled) Step 7: Begin the lab by having groups begin to drop their eggs at different heights and
recording data (in addition to egg survival) Step 8: Have students calculate potential energy & kinetic energy & momentum of their car drops (can be assisted by teacher with calculations) Step 9: Finish worksheets Step 10: Debrief Lab activity (go over lab worksheet and discuss general findings/trends)
3-4 hour lab total; 1 hour for 3D design, 3 hours maximum to conduct the lab.

The teacher MUST PRINT all the student designed egg shells
Lab area (tall location such as roof, stairs, balcony, etc.)
Labeled heights (tape, etc.)
Scales
Timer (phone apps can work too!)
Tape measure
*Knowledge of kinetic energy, potential energy, and momentum (possible to test other physical quantities)
See attached rubric for the Egg Drop Lab

https://www.pinterest.com/explore/egg-drop-project/ - Filled with pictures/resources for winning designs (non-3D printed however)

This is an upgrade to my simpler design:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:167446 New features:
-- Has screw holes for attaching to a desk
-- Has a hole for feeding the USB cable underneath
-- Has a cable guide that lets the stand sit flat on the table if the cable is running under it

The Nexus 4 wireless charger orb (http://www.amazon.com/Google-Nexus-4-Wireless-Charger/dp/B00BGSPIP2) would be awesome if it would hold the phone reliably to prevent it from slipping off. But most reviews gave it 1 star for being useless because the phone slips off and it doesn't charge anymore. I got it anyway and experienced the same problem. So I made this stand for it which holds the wireless charger upright, and has a little lip to keep it from moving around (but doesn't obstruct the device). It was designed so you can drop the phone on it both upright and sideways, and it will not only charge, but you can use it while it's charging!

description.text:
Have an old Commodore 64 cartridge that lost its case? Have a new Commodore 64 cartridge that never had a case?

This is a 2-part cartridge case that closely mimics the design and measurements of the cartridges Commodore made for the 64 in the early 80s. This design is Customizer enabled, so you can modify it in a number of ways:

  • remove debossed stripes
  • punch out label hole entirely
  • adjust length of cart based on PCB length
  • adjust position and size of PCB mounting hole, or remove it entirely
  • add support feet to the back (good for longer/heavier cartridges)

If you have other ideas for other customization parameters, feel free to contact me and I'll see what I can do.

I've also included two sets of STLs:

  • standard-c64-cartridge_*.stl — case for a standard Commodore cartridge for the 64.
  • gyruss-c64--cartridge_*.stl — case for Gyruss. Probably also works with other Parker Brothers carts for the Commodore 64.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

When printing on FDM printers I recommend printing with full support, and orienting the case with the opening on the print bed. This should be the default orientation of this model with most slicers. This orientation ensures that the support material will be entirely inside the case, so the outside will be unblemished (except inside the connector port).

I have some cartridges form my Commodore 64 that had no case -- they were just bare PCBs. One of them, Lazarian, is a standard Commodore cartridge, and I found a design, Makerboost's Commodore 64 Cartridge, that would work with it.

Not all cartridges are compatible with the standard case layout, however. For example, another cartridge I own is Gyruss, which was published by Parker Brothers. Parker Brothers used a shorter PCB than Commodore, and a different mounting hole size and position. I played around with slicing and dicing the STLs to get something that would work, but Thingiverse's Customizer doesn't support STL import. I even tried an STL to OpenSCAD converter, but the resulting source was so huge Customizer couldn't load it.

I ended up creating a new design from scratch in pure OpenSCAD. I used my Radar Rat Race cart, which still has its original case, as a source of measurements. I also made the design parametric, so that it could work in Customizer. This is the result.

Notes:

This is a very long print with these settings if placed on average print speeds. When I printed out the model shown in the pictures, it took about 6 hours to completely print out with added time to remove the rafting.

This print file is for the purpose of demonstration to a biology class that can be enhanced by the using rubber bands between the actin and myosin filaments to simulate the tension generated by muscle contraction. The print thickness, however, would have to be raised up to at least 50% to withstand the elastic forces from a regular sized rubber band.

Finished print at 15% thickness. Some of the protein ends fell a part when printed so a higher infill is suggested if there is worry of brittleness. This picture does not include other support materials including rubber bands or adhesives to demonstrate the actin/myosin sliding interaction.

As stated, I utilized an STL file of a myosin strand in addition to a few rectangles that I drew up and attached to copies of the original file. I utilized a textbook image of a sarcomere and replicated it in 3D.

Model creation process & g-coding
NGSS

Students in a biology class settings, ranging from introductory high school biology to AP biology, will be utilizing this model of a sarcomere (basic unit of striated muscle) to study and confirm knowledge about the sliding filament theory. Objectives Students will be utilizing 3D printed models of a sarcomere to complete an assignment on muscle contraction by applying knowledge that is learned from either a presentation or textbook regarding muscle contraction and verifying it in terms of structure and function using this print. Audiences Grades (7-12)
Ages (12-18)
Skill Levels (Basic, Intermediate) Subjects Science
Biology
AP Biology (molecular) Skills Learned (Standards) HS-LS1-2. Develop and use a model to illustrate the hierarchical organization of interacting systems that provide specific functions within multicellular organisms.

For this project, this is more of a tool to help visualize the sarcomere. It can be enhanced as stated above with the use of rubber bands to attach to the sliding zones of the filament to show muscle contraction. It is recommended that teachers teach the basics of sliding filament theory prior to the use of this print in conjunction with the supporting assignments.
2 hours for assignment completion;  6.5+ hours per 3D print.

  • The teacher will teach the content knowledge prior to printing out the sarcomere.

  • Teacher will hand out assignments and guide students over the theory in comparison to the model being used to evaluate that theory.
  • Students will complete and review the worksheet(s) with the teacher..

description.text:
I bought an open-stub J-pole antenna from a fellow ham radio enthusiast and it lacked a mast mount. I live in a condo, so my antenna mount consists of a bucket of cement and a 1/2" PVC pipe 'mast'. I took tonymtsai's clamp and added a bit of width to it for additional stability and overall just made it 'beefier' to handle the stress of the antenna.

The mount in its current design is sized for M8 bolts using 16mm OD washers. The pipe OD is 22mm. You will want to measure your pipe and change this if necessary. My pipe was actually 21.8mm, but I rounded it up to give myself some wiggle room and to allow for the camo tape I have covering the pipe.

description.text: I was having constant problems with bowden popping out on the filament feeder end. Inspired by owen's superb hot end clamp here is the one for the other end. Just printed it and looks to be good fit. Hoping it will solve my issues :)

• Print all 3 parts - riser, cone and cap.
  • If the bowden hasn't popped out and you still want to replace original clamp by this, simply press down on the original clamp and pull the bowden out.
  • Disassemble mechanism feeder on you Ultimaker, by unscrewing the extruder wheel, then the 4 botls holding the stepper motor.
  • Take the mechanism apart by unscrewing the 4 remaining bolts.
  • Remove the original clamp, and replace it with the raiser printed.
  • Put everything together,
  • Place the cap then the cone on the bowden, push it till the end to the raiser and screw the cap on using moderate force - the thing is pretty tough when printed using PLA and 100% fill, but use your hand only (two fingers).
    • See the photos - should be self explanatory. The cap and cone are identical to the one used in owen's Bowden Clamp for the hot end, so you should be able to reuse those part if you have them printed already. I've made the cap slightly smaller inner diameter to have a tighter fit for the thread - it works perfectly for me - if it does not for you please adjust the parameters at the top of the scad file accordingly. PS. This is the first thing I'm putting on Thingiverse - let me know if you print it :)

description.text:
This is dog waste bag holder with a threaded top. The cap has a hole for a carrying rope.
I've included the .STL file for printing, and the .123DX (Autodesk 123D Design) file for remixing.

EDIT: I've added the files for a filled waste bag clip, and a chain with swivels to connect the two together. It's a very big print that barely fits on my 5th gen print bed. You may have to split the STL for smaller beds. I've also included the .123dx (Autodesk 123D Design) files for remixing

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

10

The threads are very tight at first. They will loosen up a bit after use. After printing, the threads will have some burrs and inconsistencies. Thread the cap on one turn at a time and rotate it a few times. Clear each turn of the threads before trying to tighten it further.

I went through a lot of trial and error, mostly error, to make this design. I have been trying to learn how to draw threads in 123D Design for quite a while. This project gave me plenty of practice.

Originally, I wanted the bags to feed through the top of the holder, through the cap. It worked, but the bag spool would bind after pulling 1 or 2 bags out. Eventually, I went with a more traditional design, with an oval opening in the side.

The design iterations from left to right. The first two had threads that didn't connect. The third design was too narrow, and has an off-center cap. The fourth design is the right size, but doesn't feed more than 1-2 bags before binding. The fifth design works, and has been field tested with a German Shepard that poops a LOT.

Notes:

At 0.3mm there's very little infill and with it set to 10% it ends up solid anyway.

I was thinking of making a roller design with some aluminum angle, some bolts and roller bearings, with the spool running directly on the bearings.

Then I slid a sharp edge of a PLA print around the inside of a filament spool and noticed how slick it was.

"I could make an addon for the spool holder, much easier than anything rolling."

I went through several mental iterations, at first thinking it would have snap on pieces to keep the roll centered between two flat parts connected by a thin bridge in the middle.

In a few minutes I'd simplified it down to just a plain, thin, "U" channel the full length. Then to save on print time and filament use I cut the notches in the sides and the four holes in the top.

If it loads with the wrong size, it's supposed to be 30mm wide.
